work.\"\n    },\n    \"axioms\": [\n      {\n        \"id\": \"axiom_problem_not_prose\",\n        \"one_sentence\": \"Most writing problems are structural and argument-level, not language-level.\",\n        \"full_statement\": \"When a piece of content fails, the root cause is almost never vocabulary or phrasing. It is that the piece lacks a genuine judgment — a conclusion the reader can disagree with, a tension they feel, or a question they did not know they had. Rewriting sentences without fixing the structural void produces better-looking emptiness.\",\n        \"why\": \"Agents default to language-level suggestions (stronger verbs, shorter sentences, better transitions) because structure-level problems are invisible without editorial judgment. This axiom forces the agent to look past the surface.\",\n        \"confidence\": \"high\",\n        \"evidence_type\": [\n          \"practice_pattern\",\n          \"case_observation\"\n        ],\n        \"applies_when\": [\n          \"the user asks for content feedback, review, or 'why isn't this working'\",\n          \"the piece is structurally a discussion piece, blog post, essay, opinion article, or persuasion-oriented marketing copy\",\n          \"the user has the freedom to restructure (not just edit a fixed-form template)\"\n        ],\n        \"does_not_apply_when\": [\n          \"the task is copy editing for grammar, spelling, or compliance\",\n          \"the format is rigid (legal contracts, regulatory filings, technical reference docs)\",\n          \"the piece is informational-only by design (product specs, API docs, encyclopedia entries)\",\n          \"the user has explicitly asked only for line-level polishing\"\n        ],\n        \"failure_risk\": \"Refusing to fix sentences when the user genuinely just wants smoother prose. Lecturing about structure when the user needs a 30-minute turnaround on existing content.\",\n        \"status\": \"locked\",\n        \"human_lock\": {\n          \"by\": \"KDNA Team\",\n          \"at\": \"2026-05-27\",\n          \"statement\": \"Reviewed and locked for official writing asset release. Applies_when, does_not_apply_when, and failure_risk are intentional judgment boundaries.\",\n          \"checked\": {\n            \"applies_when\": true,\n            \"does_not_apply_when\": true,\n            \"failure_risk\": true\n          }\n        }\n      },\n      {\n        \"id\": \"axiom_judgment_pressure\",\n        \"one_sentence\": \"Every piece of content must exert judgment pressure on the reader.\",\n        \"full_statement\": \"Judgment pressure means the reader encounters a claim that is specific enough to disagree with, surprising enough to remember, or consequential enough to act on. Content that only explains, defines, or summarizes exerts zero judgment pressure and will be forgotten.\",\n        \"why\": \"Most AI-generated or AI-polished content explains concepts without taking a position. It reads well but leaves no trace. The agent must learn to distinguish between content that informs and content that changes the reader's mind.\",\n        \"confidence\": \"high\",\n        \"evidence_type\": [\n          \"practice_pattern\",\n          \"industry_consensus\"\n        ],\n        \"applies_when\": [\n          \"the piece's purpose is to change a reader's belief,",
